44 CONNECT TWEET LINKEDIN 1 COMMENT EMAIL MORE LUBBOCK, Texas — Iowa State's showdown Saturday with Texas Tech was the Cyclones' first true test against one of the Big 12 Conference's prolific Air Raid offenses.
The Cyclones failed that first test.
Iowa State was unable to shut down or keep up with the Texas Tech offense and suffered its first Big 12 loss of the season — a 66-31 defeat to the Red Raiders Saturday at Jones AT&T Stadium.
"The speed and the pace isn't going to slow down the next two weeks," said Iowa State coach Paul Rhoads. "On paper, the next two offenses are better than this one."
Too much speed on both sides of ball for Texas Tech. Sloppy ISU tackling, inconsistent offense
Iowa State fell to 2-3 overall on the season and 1-1 in conference play.
That's the bad news.
Even worse: Life doesn't get any easier for the Cyclones, who now get ready for the toughest part of their schedule when they host second-ranked Texas Christian and then travel to third-ranked Baylor.
DES MOINES REGISTER
ISU takeaways: Cyclones set records, both good and bad
Texas Tech began the day ranked third in the nation in scoring offense, averaging 50.0 points per game. The only two teams better than the Red Raiders in that category: Baylor and TCU.
The Red Raiders lived up to their fast-scoring, run-and-gun reputation by tallying a school-record 776 yards of total offense (515 passing, 261 rushing). Texas Tech quarterback Patrick Mahomes completed 33 of 46 passes for 428 yards and five touchdowns.
"He's a mighty fine quarterback," Rhoads said.
One of the few bright spots on the day: Iowa State's rushing attack, which produced for the third straight game. Leading the way was redshirt freshman Mike Warren, who continued to etch his named throughout Iowa State's record book.
PETERSON: Save for Warren, nothing works for Cyclones​
Warren, who broke his own single-game school rushing record for a freshman with 245 yards, also broke the freshman season record just five games in. He passed Stevie Hick's mark of 471 yards set in 2003 and also became the first freshman in school history to run for at least 100 yards in three games.
Warren celebrated the news by thanking his offensive line.
"I went to my O-line and just gave them all a big hug," Warren said. "I was just really surprised that I was able to accomplish that with those guys."
Mike on what is next and how he celebrated record performance.
He wasn't the only running back to have success, either. Iowa State running back Joshua Thomas scored twice in the first half with two 1-yard rushing touchdowns.
The running success, and the switch to a three-man front to help combat Air Raid offenses, wasn't enough to keep up with the Red Raiders.
"We just didn't tackle well," said Iowa State safety Kamari Cotton-Moya. "We just didn't execute."
Kamari Cotton-Moya talks defense and more.
The problems weren't limited to the defense. Iowa State quarterback Sam Richardson completed just 10 of 21 passes for 139 yards with one touchdown and three interceptions. Backup quarterback Joel Lanning, who has been brought in at times and used in mostly running situations, took over in the fourth quarter.
"Sam was not having one of his better days and we got Joel snaps," Rhoads said. "He hasn't had a chance to really go out there play quarterback and run the offense. We wanted to get him snaps."
DES MOINES REGISTER
ISU status report: Struggles key Red Raiders rout
Rhoads said that Richardson would be Iowa State's quarterback moving forward and the three-man front would stay. One change that could come: at kicker where Cole Netten missed another field goal — this one from 40 yards. He made his only other attempt from 20 yards, but Chris Francis came in to kick the extra point on a fourth-quarter touchdown.
Rhoads was asked if the kicking job was open.
"Probably is," Rhoads said. "We'll probably kick all week to see who's that guy."
One thing is for sure: things are probably going to get even more difficult with Iowa State's next two opponents.
"I think everybody's just frustrated and disappointed in themselves because they know that we could have played a lot better," said Iowa State wide receiver Allen Lazard. "We lost to a good team today but we didn't play as well as our potential."
Inconsistency put too much stress on the Cyclones defense
